<font color="#FF0000">U.S. WAR CRIMES</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec  6  5:51:24 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I was &quot;in country&quot; from July '67 to April '69. After I got my draft notice, I enlisted for 3 years so I'd have &quot;choice, not chance&quot;. I didn't want to get sent to Viet Nam. After 10 months of training and Stateside duty, enduring the reprehensible behaviour of the American public(being refused service or having to pay in advance in restaurants from coast to coast), I volunteered for Viet Nam. After my first tour, I extended my tour to take advantage of the 5 month &quot;early out&quot; being offered. I had a desk job most of the time. Had it pretty good, even during the '68 Tet Offensive, when I traded my typewriter for an M-60. I never had any illusions about how good I had it. Didn't have to look far to find a GI or Vietnamese who was much worse off. Always considered myself pretty lucky. Through the years, I maintained the same attitude. &quot;I had it pretty good, many other men and women on both sides had it much, much worse.&quot; It wasn't until I saw the movie &quot;The Deerhunter&quot; many years ago, that I discovered the people who had it worse than anyone were the friends and families of those of us who were over there. It might have gotten pretty sticky where we were, but at least we knew what was going on. Those at home, didn't know from minute to minute or day to day if we were alive, wounded, dead or missing. Some people, to this day, don't know what happened to their fathers, sons, brothers, husbands, daughters, wives. At what point could they have said, &quot;All right, he/she isn't coming back. I'm going to mourn, but I have to get on with my life.&quot;? When is that time? After one year, three, five, ten, twenty, THIRTY GODDAMN YEARS? When should a woman who was twenty years old then and fifty years old now have said, &quot;He's dead, he's not coming back. I love him, I miss him. Life goes on.&quot;? Who can possibly answer that?<br>
I accuse the United States Government past, present, and future of war crimes against the citizens of Viet Nam and the United States of America. I accuse the Government of the most heinous, malicious and brutal behaviour imaginable to satisfy the maniacal and perverse cravings of the Military-Industrial Complex about which Eisenhower warned us.<br><br>
Thanks for the use of this site. What a great soapbox!<br><br>
           WELCOME HOME VIETNAM VETS!!!<br><br>
Neal Pollack<br>
SP/5 US Army<br>
1st Logistical Command<br>
July '67-April '69
